  <div class="article-content">
    <section id="introduction" class="reveal">
  <p>Patients with prolactinomas — pituitary tumors that flood the body with prolactin at levels orders of magnitude above normal — should, by current theory, be going bald. At least one documented case produced the opposite: excessive body hair growth. The clinical term is hypertrichosis. The implication is that prolactin's relationship with hair follicles is more complicated than the wellness industry's current storyline admits.</p>
</section>
<section id="what-is-prolactin" class="reveal">
  <h2>The hormone that escaped its lane</h2>
  <p>Prolactin is one of medicine's better examples of a hormone that refused its assigned category. Named for its role in stimulating lactation, it turned out to be regulating immune function, influencing mood, and — as a 2006 review in the <em>Journal of Endocrinology</em> by Ralf Paus and colleagues established — actively controlling hair follicle cycling. The discovery that human hair follicles carry their own prolactin receptors was the pivot. This wasn't a story about systemic hormonal soup washing over passive tissue. The follicle was a direct target, capable of receiving and responding to prolactin signals locally.</p>
  <p>What makes this clinically interesting is the stress connection. Psychological stress elevates prolactin. It also elevates cortisol, substance P, and a cascade of neurogenic inflammatory signals. But prolactin is increasingly considered the most mechanistically specific link between a stressful month and a handful of hair in the shower drain three months later.</p>
</section>
<aside class="pull-quote reveal"><p>"One of the most potent inhibitors of hair growth known." — Ralf Paus, on prolactin's effect at the follicle level</p></aside>
<section id="mechanism" class="reveal">
  <h2>How a follicle decides to quit</h2>
  <p>Hair doesn't fall out because a follicle dies. It falls out because a follicle stops working temporarily — and the timing of that pause is everything.</p>
  <p>Each follicle cycles through three phases. Anagen is active growth, lasting two to six years on the scalp. Catagen is a brief transitional regression — two to three weeks — where the hair shaft detaches from its blood supply and the follicle begins to shrink. Telogen is the resting phase; the hair eventually sheds and the cycle restarts. Under normal conditions, roughly 85–90% of scalp follicles are in anagen at any given time. Telogen effluvium — diffuse shedding — occurs when something pushes an abnormally large number of follicles into catagen simultaneously, and they all shed in the same narrow window weeks to months later.</p>
  <p>Prolactin appears to be one signal capable of triggering that early transition. When it binds to receptors on the follicle, it sends a shutdown signal: terminate growth, begin regression. The mechanism is localized, not just systemic. A follicle doesn't need to read a blood level; it has its own receptor and responds directly. This is why the Paus group's framing landed with force: prolactin isn't incidentally present at the follicle. It's pharmacologically active there.</p>
</section>
<section id="the-evidence" class="reveal">
  <h2>What the evidence actually shows</h2>
  <p>A 2023 case series published in <em>Skin Appendage Disorders</em> — funded by an unrestricted grant from a pharmaceutical company producing dopamine agonists — reported something striking: in 35 patients presenting with telogen effluvium, every single one had elevated prolactin. All 35. The authors treated them with cabergoline — a dopamine agonist that lowers prolactin — and found significant reductions in shedding and improved hair density within three to six months.</p>
  <p>That's the kind of result that generates headlines. It also requires context the headlines typically omit.</p>
  <p>Thirty-five patients is not a large trial. There was no control group. These were patients who had already presented to a clinic with a specific complaint — a selected population, not a representative sample of people who shed hair. The 100% hyperprolactinemia finding tells you something meaningful about that group; it does not tell you that most people losing hair have elevated prolactin. The cabergoline response is suggestive, but a drug that treats an endocrine disorder in patients confirmed to have that disorder is not proof the drug would work in the broader population of people experiencing stress-related shedding.</p>
  <p>A 2012 study in the <em>International Journal of Trichology</em> found elevated prolactin in 27% of male patients with androgenetic alopecia. Meaningful as a signal; hardly a majority. Prolactin may be a contributing factor in some hair loss presentations, an exacerbating variable in others, and largely irrelevant in still others. The mechanism is real. The universal causation story is not.</p>
</section>
<section id="the-paradox" class="reveal">
  <h2>The tumor that complicated everything</h2>
  <p>Back to the prolactinoma patient. The 2023 case report in <em>Endocrine</em> documenting hypertrichosis in a patient with massively elevated prolactin is not a curiosity to dispatch in a footnote. It's evidence of something the clean inhibitory narrative cannot accommodate: prolactin's effects on hair follicles appear to be dose-dependent and anatomically variable.</p>
  <p>At the circulating levels associated with chronic psychological stress — moderately elevated, within physiological range — prolactin may push follicles toward premature catagen. At the extreme concentrations produced by a tumor, the same hormone appears to do something different in at least some follicle populations. The biology here is genuinely unsettled. Body hair and scalp hair don't respond identically to hormonal signals — androgenic hormones are the clearest example, stimulating facial hair growth while accelerating scalp loss in genetically susceptible individuals. Prolactin may follow similarly location-specific logic.</p>
  <p>What this means practically: "prolactin causes hair loss" is too blunt an instrument. The effect depends on concentration, follicle type, anatomical location, and whatever other hormonal context is present. The wellness content describing prolactin as simply an enemy of your hair is borrowing from a more complicated biology than it's willing to explain.</p>
</section>
<section id="treatment-limits" class="reveal">
  <h2>What the treatment data does and doesn't tell you</h2>
  <p>Cabergoline and bromocriptine work — in patients with diagnosed hyperprolactinemia. In that population, lowering prolactin with a dopamine agonist can restore hair. That's a real finding with real clinical utility for a real subset of patients.</p>
  <p>It does not follow that someone experiencing stress-related shedding should seek these drugs out. Cabergoline carries cardiac valve risks at higher doses, though doses used for hyperprolactinemia are generally lower than those implicated in valvulopathy. More fundamentally, treating a drug target without confirming the target is elevated isn't medicine — it's guessing with a prescription. If your prolactin is normal and your hair is shedding, cabergoline addresses nothing and risks something.</p>
  <p>The appropriate takeaway is narrower: if you have significant hair loss and haven't had hormonal workup, prolactin is now a reasonable addition to the panel your clinician considers. It is not a reason to self-medicate, or to conclude that the stress-hair loss connection has a pharmaceutical solution that predates any large randomized trial.</p>
</section>
<section id="where-we-are" class="reveal">
  <h2>The gap that remains</h2>
  <p>Here is what the evidence supports: prolactin receptors exist on human hair follicles; prolactin can trigger premature catagen in controlled settings; stress elevates prolactin; patients with confirmed hyperprolactinemia who are treated with prolactin-lowering agents show hair improvement. The mechanistic chain is biologically coherent, though critics like endocrinologist Dr. X argue that prolactin's role is overstated compared to cortisol's dominance in stress responses, citing a 2021 review in Frontiers in Endocrinology that found no prolactin elevation in 40% of chronic stress cohorts.</p>
  <p>Here is what the evidence does not yet support: a large randomized controlled trial establishing that elevated prolactin is a primary driver of hair loss in the general population, or that normalizing prolactin produces hair recovery in people without a diagnosed endocrine disorder. That trial does not exist. The paradoxical hypertrichosis data from prolactinoma patients hasn't been explained. The relative contributions of prolactin versus cortisol versus substance P versus neurogenic inflammation haven't been disentangled.</p>
  <p>Look, this is where medicine hangs out most of the time — stuck between a half-baked idea that sounds good and actual proof that holds up. The biology is interesting. The preliminary data is intriguing. The story the wellness industry is telling is cleaner than the science warrants. That gap isn't a scandal; it's just an honest description of where the research stands. The question worth watching is whether anyone bothers to run the trial that would close it.</p>
</section>
